external_knowledge:
- A "time series" represents a sequence of data points recorded at successive times;
- "forecast_date" is the date when the forecast was made;
- "forecast_value" is the predicted value for the time series;
- "latest_forecast" is a row number indicating the most recent forecast for each time series.

- Forecast accuracy is often measured by the average difference (or error) between forecasted values and actual values;
- A lower average difference indicates higher forecast accuracy;
- The `ts_id` uniquely identifies each time series in the dataset.

sql:
SELECT frequency, COUNT(DISTINCT ts_id) AS unique_time_series_count
FROM ts_metadata
GROUP BY frequency;

external_knowledge:
- "Most influential features" refers to features with the highest values;
- "Shining star" is a metaphor for the top-ranked feature;
- "Constellation of data points" represents the collection of models and their features.

- Confidence interval > 0.7 indicates a higher level of trust in the forecast;
- The latest forecast for each model is used to calculate the average forecast accuracy;
- Models are ranked by their average forecast accuracy in descending order.

- "top 3 models" refers to the models with the highest accuracy for each time series;
- "accuracy" is a measure of how well the model predicts the time series data;
- "average forecast value" is the mean of the forecast values for a given model and time series.

- "Top performers" refers to models with the highest forecast accuracy for each time series dataset;
- "Overall accuracy" refers to the average forecast accuracy across all time series datasets;
- "Number of datasets" refers to the count of distinct time series datasets each model has been trained on.

- "wise analysts" refers to users with the role of 'analyst';
- "sowing seeds of ARIMA forecasts" refers to making forecasts using the ARIMA model type;
- "more than 10 seeds" means the user has made more than 10 forecasts.

- 'high forecast accuracy' refers to models with an average forecast accuracy greater than 0.8;
- 'features' are characteristics or attributes of the data, such as mean, standard deviation, or skewness;
- 'models' are predictive or analytical constructs used to forecast or understand data patterns;
- 'datasets' are collections of time series data that are analyzed using the models and features.
